title: Grateful Dead Live at Oakland Auditorium Arena on 1979-08-05
description: Mississippi Half Step-> Franklin's Tower-> Me & My Uncle-> Big River, Candyman, It's All Over Now, Brown Eyed Women, Lost Sailor-> Althea-> Promised Land Scarlet Begonias-> Fire On The Mountain, Estimated Prophet-> Eyes Of The World-> Drums-> Ollin Arrageed*-> Not Fade Away-> Wharf Rat-> Around & Around, E:Bertha-> E: Good Lovin', E: Johnny B. Goode**

reviews.review_text:
bomb! Really great SBD copy of this sick show.
Phil comin' in strong too

nice upgrades This show, as well as the previous night's show, are nice upgrades to what's been floating around in trading circles for years. I was at both shows and these recordings bring back fond memories. Love Brent's contributions. Miss that guy!!
Where's the Ollin Arageed? Nice show but the main reason I downloaded it, Ollin Arageed, was missing.

Great quality Great tunes and super quality.

Here's some cover-art for this show:
http://www.toddalbert.com/music/cover_art/

Sure it was better to be there There are some tech glitches with this and parts are missing (ollin arrageed) + the first set is just ok... show does not really get going till est>eyes and from then on throws some serious heat nfa>wharf rat>arnd very very hot.

Great sounding show But---- The show sounds great and the boys are on but, somebody needed to point out that the Althea gets cut at the end. And it's a brutal cut at that.  If you know anything about 79 Altheas' they are hot and this cut needed to be brought to the attention of the people. However it's still worth getting.
Althea Cut You the man Jeff!  I was ready.

One of the best of the year, but recording has gaps This is a good show from start to finish, including the first set, which has very nice Franklin's Tower. (Brent's "Captain and Tennille" electric piano sounds more like "Muskrat Love" than Brown Eyed Women and Lost Sailor, but it's not too distracting.) I like this Fire and the Estimated Prophet is excellent.

Unfortunately, there are a number of cuts in some of the songs. Ollin Arrageed is completely missing, which is a shame. You can hear the opening beats of Ollin at the end of Drums, but Ollin never appears.

Still, this is an enjoyable, musical show to listen too. It's better than the previous night, and is one of the better shows of 1979.
Heady Jamming Personally, I like this show better than some of the Dick's Picks. Jerry is feeling it this night you can tell. Wish I could get a complete SBD.

bread crumb I was intrigued to hear the Lost Sailor > Althea which turns out to be more sequential the linkage.  A kind of, "let's play the new songs" rather than "I wonder if there is path from one to the other."  

I continue to muse on the half-step > franklin's show opener.  Half-step is such an upbeat tune with such decidely gloomy lyrics - following it with a song of unrepentant hope provides a sort of meta-physical balance.  

Last thought.  Scarlet > Fire, Estimated > Eyes was the holy grail of second sets in the early eighties.  It was not invented with Brent in the band, but they sure perfected it.
